":"1124","1135":"1135","1057":"1057","Dachau, Oberbayern, Bavaria, Germany":"Dachau, Bavaria, Germany","Scheyern, Pfaffenhofen, Bavaria, Germany":"Scheyern, Pfaffenhofen, Bavaria, Germany","nameMeanings":[{"name":"von","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of Welsh   Vaughan  .","Chinese: variant of   Wong  .","Cambodian: written វ៉ុន, unexplained."],"variants":[{"name":"Vaughan","meanings":["Welsh: from <i>fychan</i>, a lenited form of <i>bychan</i>, a diminutive of <i>bach</i> ‘little’. This was often used to distinguish the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, typically the son of a father with the same name."]}]},{"name":"Otto","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a short form of any of the various Germanic compound personal names containing the element <i>od</i>, <i>ot</i> ‘prosperity, wealth’ (  compare the corresponding Old English <i>ēad</i> in names such as  Edward   and   Edwin  ).  St Otto of Bamberg  (  d. 1139 ) was a missionary to the Pomeranians.  Otto the Great  (  912–73 ) is generally regarded as the founder of the Holy Roman Empire, and the name has been borne by several members of German and Austrian royal houses. It was recorded occasionally among immigrants to England from the Low Countries in the 14th century, but failed to establish itself. Since the 19th century it has again been used occasionally in the English-speaking world, mostly among immigrants from Germanic countries."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Graf Otto I von Dachau-Valley was born about 1085, in Scheyern, Pfaffenhofen, Bavaria, Germany, his father, Arnold I Von Scheyern, was 29 and his mother, Beatrix von Reipersberg, was 27. He married Adelheid Von Weilheim. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 2 daughters. He died on 1 August 1135, at the age of 51."},"et":{"about 1085–1 Au